Lockman SWIRE master catalogueÂ¶

Preparation of Red Cluster Sequence Lensing Survey (RCSLenS) dataÂ¶

This catalogue comes from dmu0_RCSLenS.

In the catalogue, we keep:

  • The id as unique object identifier;
  • The position;
  • The g, r, i, z, y auto magnitudes.

imported_columns = OrderedDict({
        "id": "rcs_id",
        "ALPHA_J2000": "rcs_ra",
        "DELTA_J2000": "rcs_dec",
        "CLASS_STAR": "rcs_stellarity",
        "MAG_g": "m_rcs_g",
        "MAGERR_g": "merr_rcs_g",
        "MAG_r": "m_rcs_r",
        "MAGERR_r": "merr_rcs_r",        
        "MAG_i": "m_rcs_i",
        "MAGERR_i": "merr_rcs_i",
        "MAG_z": "m_rcs_z",
        "MAGERR_z": "merr_rcs_z",
        "MAG_y": "m_rcs_y",
        "MAGERR_y": "merr_rcs_y"    
    })


catalogue = Table.read("../../dmu0/dmu0_RCSLenS/data/RCSLenS_Lockman-SWIRE.fits")[list(imported_columns)]
for column in imported_columns:
    catalogue[column].name = imported_columns[column]

epoch = 2017

# Clean table metadata
catalogue.meta = None
In [5]:
# Adding flux and band-flag columns
for col in catalogue.colnames:
    if col.startswith('m_'):
        
        errcol = "merr{}".format(col[1:])
        #Replace 99.0 and -99.0 with nan
        catalogue[col][catalogue[col] == 99.0] = np.nan
        catalogue[col][catalogue[col] == -99.0] = np.nan
        catalogue[errcol][catalogue[errcol] == 99.0] = np.nan
        catalogue[errcol][catalogue[errcol] == -99.0] = np.nan
        
        flux, error = mag_to_flux(np.array(catalogue[col]), np.array(catalogue[errcol]))
        
        # Fluxes are added in µJy
        catalogue.add_column(Column(flux * 1.e6, name="f{}".format(col[1:])))
        catalogue.add_column(Column(error * 1.e6, name="f{}".format(errcol[1:])))

        #We add NAN filled aperture columns because no aperture fluxes are present
        nancol = np.zeros(len(catalogue))
        nancol.fill(np.nan)
        catalogue.add_column(Column(nancol, 
                                    name="m_ap{}".format(col[1:])))
        catalogue.add_column(Column(nancol, 
                                    name="merr_ap{}".format(col[1:])))
        catalogue.add_column(Column(nancol, 
                                    name="f_ap{}".format(col[1:])))
        catalogue.add_column(Column(nancol, 
                                    name="ferr_ap{}".format(col[1:])))
        
        # Band-flag column
        if 'ap' not in col:
            catalogue.add_column(Column(np.zeros(len(catalogue), dtype=bool), name="flag{}".format(col[1:])))
        
# TODO: Set to True the flag columns for fluxes that should not be used for SED fitting.

II - Removal of duplicated sourcesÂ¶

We remove duplicated objects from the input catalogues.

In [7]:
SORT_COLS = []
FLAG_NAME = 'rcs_flag_cleaned'

nb_orig_sources = len(catalogue)

catalogue = remove_duplicates(
    catalogue, RA_COL, DEC_COL, 
    sort_col= SORT_COLS,
    flag_name=FLAG_NAME)

nb_sources = len(catalogue)

print("The initial catalogue had {} sources.".format(nb_orig_sources))
print("The cleaned catalogue has {} sources ({} removed).".format(nb_sources, nb_orig_sources - nb_sources))
print("The cleaned catalogue has {} sources flagged as having been cleaned".format(np.sum(catalogue[FLAG_NAME])))

The initial catalogue had 2607590 sources.
The cleaned catalogue has 2519719 sources (87871 removed).
The cleaned catalogue has 86826 sources flagged as having been cleaned

III - Astrometry correctionÂ¶

We match the astrometry to the Gaia one. We limit the Gaia catalogue to sources with a g band flux between the 30th and the 70th percentile. Some quick tests show that this give the lower dispersion in the results.

In [8]:
gaia = Table.read("../../dmu0/dmu0_GAIA/data/GAIA_Lockman-SWIRE.fits")
gaia_coords = SkyCoord(gaia['ra'], gaia['dec'])
